    "preface": {
      "@id": "preface",
      "dc:title": "*IMPORTANT",
      "@type": "vdoc:Chapter",
      "vdoc:content": [
        "This document, like most of the more principled and less pragmatic\n    documents must be understood as strong speculation and as an\n    architectural exercise (although a very serious one) on\n    what-could-be.",
        null,
        "    This rings especially true for the primary focus of this document,\n    ie. for ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "ValOS Core"
          ]
        },
        " as the fully functional open source\n    core around which the often proprietary ValOS ecosystem would expand.\n    This is an ambitious, even presumptuous attempt to facilitate the\n    fruitful side-by-side living of open source communities as well as\n    private enterprises as a combination of technical and social\n    architecture.",
        null,
        "    (The technical part is the ambitious part and the social part is\n    the presumptuous part. :D)"
      ]
    },
    "specification": {
      "@id": "specification",
      "dc:title": "ValOS specification",
      "@type": "vdoc:Chapter",
      "vdoc:content": [
        "This document has two purposes. Firstly it provides the initial\n    specification of Valaa Open System (",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "ValOS"
          ]
        },
        ") and secondly\n    it serves as the introduction for ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:Reference",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "Development Operations"
          ],
          "vdoc:ref": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DevOps"
        },
        ".",
        null,
        "    ValOS specification is provided as quoted and numbered ValOS rules.",
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-1.1"
              ]
            },
            ": ",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "ValOS packages"
              ]
            },
            "are\n        all the npmjs.com packages with ",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "@valos"
              ]
            },
            " scope which\n        don't have cyclic dependencies with other ",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "@valos"
              ]
            },
            " scope packages."
          ]
        },
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-1.2"
              ]
            },
            ": Valaa Open System (",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "ValOS"
              ]
            },
            " is defined to be the contents of all ValOS\n        packages and nothing else."
          ]
        },
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-1.3"
              ]
            },
            ": ",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "ValOS specification"
              ]
            },
            " consists of all files in all ValOS packages whose path in the\n        package matches the JS regex ",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "/^specifications\\/\\w*.md$/"
              ]
            },
            " and nothing else."
          ]
        },
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-1.4"
              ]
            },
            ": Rules in a package are\n        considered to be more specific than the rules in its package\n        dependency tree. More specific rules take precedence."
          ]
        },
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-1.5"
              ]
            },
            ": All packages which conform to\n        ValOS specification are called ",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "ValOS packages"
              ]
            },
            ". These\n        packages are inclusively considered part of the ",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "ValOS ecosystem"
              ]
            },
            "."
          ]
        },
        "The system is structured into a plethora of purpose-oriented\n    vertical ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "domains"
          ]
        },
        " and into four content oriented\n    horizontal ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "utility layers"
          ]
        },
        ".",
        null,
        "    Each utility layer is named by the content or service is provides\n    and builds or depends on the previous layers.",
        {
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:BulletList",
              "vdoc:entries": [
                [
                  {
                    "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
                    "vdoc:content": [
                      "files"
                    ]
                  },
                  " layer provides files via git repositories."
                ],
                [
                  {
                    "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
                    "vdoc:content": [
                      "packages"
                    ]
                  },
                  " layer provides npm packages via npm registry.\n        These packages are created by git repositories called ",
                  {
                    "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
                    "vdoc:content": [
                      "vaults"
                    ]
                  },
                  "."
                ],
                [
                  {
                    "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
                    "vdoc:content": [
                      "authorities"
                    ]
                  },
                  " layer provides the ValOS live authority\n        service APIs. Authorities are deployed and managed with ",
                  {
                    "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
                    "vdoc:content": [
                      "opspace"
                    ]
                  },
                  " workspaces."
                ],
                [
                  {
                    "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
                    "vdoc:content": [
                      "partitions"
                    ]
                  },
                  " layer provides the resource content as\n        partition events and bvobs. These are served via authority\n        service APIs."
                ]
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        "",
        null,
        "    TODO(iridian): Figure out and describe the concrete role of domains.\n    NOTE(iridian, 2019-08): Domains are now mostly figured out; they\n    are administrative, organisational units and namespaces.",
        null,
        "    A DevOp manages these layers by scripts that are delivered inside\n    the packages alongside their main content. A command line tool\n    called ValOS Medium or ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "vlm"
          ]
        },
        " is used to discover and ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "invoke"
          ]
        },
        " these scripts as ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "valma commands"
          ]
        },
        ".",
        null,
        "    From a DevOps perspective ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "valma"
          ]
        },
        ", ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "vault"
          ]
        },
        " and ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "opspace"
          ]
        },
        " are the three concrete core mechanisms that\n    everything else ties into.",
        null,
        "    Valma and specific domains are specified in other documents and as such\n    are only briefly described here.\n    The utility layers are common to everything form the bulk of this\n    document. They are fully specified at the last part of this document\n    after all the brief descriptions."
      ]
    },
    "domains": {
      "@id": "domains",
      "dc:title": "ValOS `domains` are cross-stack slices, each with a well-defined purpose",
      "@type": "vdoc:Chapter",
      "vdoc:content": [
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-2.1"
              ]
            },
            ": A ",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "domain"
              ]
            },
            " is the\n        collection of all the systems, interactions and dynamics which\n        exclusively serve a particular purpose."
          ]
        },
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-2.2"
              ]
            },
            ": A domain must define the\n        purpose, describe its producers and consumers and should\n        provide a direction for technical and operational structure as\n        well."
          ]
        },
        "For example the ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:Reference",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "@valos/kernel"
          ],
          "vdoc:ref": "@valos/kernel"
        },
        " domain provides the\n    essential central ValOS code for developing new ValOS\n    infrastructure software. Its main producers are the kernel software\n    developers and its consumers are the infrastructure software\n    developers. It revolves around developing code as library packages."
      ]
    },
    "valma": {
      "@id": "valma",
      "dc:title": "`valma` - a convenience CLI to context-dependent command scripts",
      "@type": "vdoc:Chapter",
      "vdoc:content": [
        "valma (",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "vlm"
          ]
        },
        " in CLI) is a convenience tool for executing\n    command scripts exported by packages in valos workspace contexts.\n    It is a generalization of 'npx -c' behaviour, adding\n    discoverability, ability to invoke global scripts and the ability\n    to invoke multiple scripts at once using glob matching.",
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-3.1"
              ]
            },
            ": valma is installed with ",
            {
              "@type": "revdoc:Command",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "npm install -g valma"
              ]
            },
            " or as a package dependency"
          ]
        },
        "This installs the global CLI command ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "vlm"
          ]
        },
        ". At its core\n    valma is a command dispatcher to ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "valma scripts"
          ]
        },
        " in\n    various ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "command pools"
          ]
        },
        ".",
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-3.2"
              ]
            },
            ": valma searches the scripts\n        first from the package.json ",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "scripts"
              ]
            },
            " pool, then from ",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "./node_modules/.bin/"
              ]
            },
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "depends"
              ]
            },
            " pool and lastly from\n        the OS-specific variant of ",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "/usr/bin"
              ]
            },
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "global"
              ]
            },
            " pool."
          ]
        },
        "As an example typing ",
        {
          "@type": "revdoc:Command",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "vlm status"
          ]
        },
        " in some directory\n    context would forward the command to ",
        {
          "@type": "revdoc:Command",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "valma.bin/valma-status"
          ]
        },
        " first if one exists and falling back to the more generic versions\n    if not. The call eventually resolves at the global ",
        {
          "@type": "revdoc:Command",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "/usr/bin/valma-status"
          ]
        },
        ". Its implementation then calls ",
        {
          "@type": "revdoc:Command",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "vlm .status/**/*"
          ]
        },
        " which calls all scripts which match\n    the glob ",
        {
          "@type": "revdoc:Command",
          "vdoc:content": [
            ".valma-status/**/*"
          ]
        },
        " and are visible on the\n    execution context pools (the scripts called by ",
        {
          "@type": "revdoc:Command",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "vlm status"
          ]
        },
        " are known as ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "valma status scripts"
          ]
        },
        ").",
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-3.3"
              ]
            },
            ": A package can export valma scripts using npm package.json ",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "bin"
              ]
            },
            " section and by prefixing the exported name with ",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valma-"
              ]
            },
            " as usual. These scripts will be available for\n        all packages depending on this package in their ",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "depends"
              ]
            },
            " pool."
          ]
        },
        "Running ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "vlm"
          ]
        },
        " with no arguments lists all available\n    commands grouped by pool in current directory context.",
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-3.5"
              ]
            },
            ": valma can be used in programmatic contexts to run valma\n        scripts. When done so, valma must be added as a dependency."
          ]
        },
        "This happens just like with the CLI by using ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "vlm <command> [<args>]"
          ]
        },
        ".\n    (\"npx -c\" would be the alternative but it's slow and limited).",
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-3.5.1"
              ]
            },
            ": valma ensures that node environment is loaded"
          ]
        },
        "The environment is loaded only once even for recursive script\n    invokations.",
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-3.5.2"
              ]
            },
            ": valma ensures that 'vlm' is always found in path"
          ]
        },
        "This is so that valma scripts can call 'vlm' even valma is not\n    globally installed as long as valma has been installed as a dependency.",
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-3.5.3"
              ]
            },
            ": valma ensures that the most specific 'vlm' version is used\n        to evaluate a command, preferring scripts over depended over global."
          ]
        },
        "This is so that toolkits can precisely control the whole toolchain\n    in their dependencies."
      ]
    },
    "utility_layer": {
      "@id": "utility_layer",
      "dc:title": "ValOS `utility` layers provide operational services",
      "@type": "vdoc:Chapter",
      "vdoc:content": [
        "ValOS has four main utility layers: ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "files"
          ]
        },
        ", ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "packages"
          ]
        },
        ", ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "authorities"
          ]
        },
        " and ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "partitions"
          ]
        },
        ". These layers\n      form the core operational infrastructure of ValOS.",
        {
          "@id": "utility_layer_overview"
        },
        {
          "@id": "files_layer"
        },
        {
          "@id": "packages_layer"
        },
        {
          "@id": "authorities_layer"
        },
        {
          "@id": "partitions_layer"
        }
      ]
