    "utility_layer_overview": {
      "@id": "utility_layer_overview",
      "dc:title": "Overview of utility layers",
      "@type": "vdoc:Chapter",
      "vdoc:content": [
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-4.1.1"
              ]
            },
            ": An ",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "utility"
              ]
            },
            " is\n          a domain with a well-defined operational purpose."
          ]
        },
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-4.1.2"
              ]
            },
            ": utility must explicitly\n          define the ",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "payload"
              ]
            },
            " it provides to its consumers as\n          well as the providers, tools and workflows used to manage\n          that payload."
          ]
        },
        "Below is a rough correlation of similar concepts across utilities.",
        {
          "vdoc:headers": [
            "Utility",
            "Tool",
            "Payload",
            "Providers",
            "Consumed via",
            "Upstream",
            "Configuration",
            "Modified via",
            "Produced via",
            "Authority",
            "Distributed via"
          ],
          "vdoc:entries": [
            [
              "files",
              "`git`",
              "files in `./*`",
              "github.com",
              "`git clone`",
              "N/A",
              "`.git/*`",
              "`branch` `commit`",
              "`git push` & PR",
              "human",
              "merge PR to & `git push master`"
            ],
            [
              "packages",
              "`vlm`, `yarn`",
              "files in `/node_modules/..`",
              "npmjs.com",
              "`depend` `require`",
              "`files`",
              "`package.json`",
              "ups. `src/*` `bin/*`",
              "upstream",
              "hybrid",
              "`assemble-packages` `publish-packages`"
            ],
            [
              "authorities",
              "`vlm`",
              "APIs, site & gateway files",
              "IaaS, custom",
              "browsers, various",
              "`files`",
              "upstream *",
              "upstream *",
              "upstream",
              "hybrid",
              "`build-release` `deploy-release`"
            ],
            [
              "partitions",
              "`vlm`, gateway",
              "event logs, bvobs",
              "authorities",
              "event & bvob APIs",
              "N/A",
              "N/A",
              "gateway",
              "command & bvob APIs",
              "authorities",
              "automatic, custom"
            ]
          ]
        },
        null,
        {
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:BulletList",
              "vdoc:entries": [
                [
                  {
                    "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
                    "vdoc:content": [
                      "Utility"
                    ]
                  },
                  "- the utility layer which is being described"
                ],
                [
                  {
                    "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
                    "vdoc:content": [
                      "Tool"
                    ]
                  },
                  " - the name of the tool used to manipulate the payload and/or metadata"
                ],
                [
                  {
                    "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
                    "vdoc:content": [
                      "Payload"
                    ]
                  },
                  " - the content or the service the utility delivers to consumers"
                ],
                [
                  {
                    "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
                    "vdoc:content": [
                      "Providers"
                    ]
                  },
                  " - the authoritative source for the payload"
                ],
                [
                  {
                    "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
                    "vdoc:content": [
                      "Consumed via"
                    ]
                  },
                  " - the mechanism used by a consumer to access the payload"
                ],
                [
                  {
                    "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
                    "vdoc:content": [
                      "Upstream"
                    ]
                  },
                  " - the possible external source of payload updates"
                ],
                [
                  {
                    "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
                    "vdoc:content": [
                      "Configuration"
                    ]
                  },
                  " - where the configuration of the utility itself is specified"
                ],
                [
                  {
                    "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
                    "vdoc:content": [
                      "Modifed via"
                    ]
                  },
                  " - how to make local changes to the payload"
                ],
                [
                  {
                    "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
                    "vdoc:content": [
                      "Produced via"
                    ]
                  },
                  " - how to request for a set of local changes to be distributed"
                ],
                [
                  {
                    "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
                    "vdoc:content": [
                      "Authority"
                    ]
                  },
                  " - who accepts and distributes a change request"
                ],
                [
                  {
                    "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
                    "vdoc:content": [
                      "Distributed via"
                    ]
                  },
                  " - how changes are made live to all consumers"
                ]
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        "Note that ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "files"
          ]
        },
        " and ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "partitions"
          ]
        },
        " don't have\n      an external upstream and thus these bands are the defining\n      authority of all of their payload.",
        null,
        "      On the other hand ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "packages"
          ]
        },
        " and ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "authorities"
          ]
        },
        " use the ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "files"
          ]
        },
        " as their external upstream: their payload is\n      generated from the content in git repositories. Making updates to\n      such utility content thus requires:",
        null,
        {
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:NumberedList",
              "vdoc:entries": [
                [
                  "modifying the corresponding upstream git repository"
                ],
                [
                  "distributing the git changes (a PR followed with ",
                  {
                    "@type": "revdoc:Command",
                    "vdoc:content": [
                      "git push master"
                    ]
                  },
                  ")"
                ],
                [
                  "distributing the utility update (",
                  {
                    "@type": "revdoc:Command",
                    "vdoc:content": [
                      "publish-packages"
                    ]
                  },
                  " or ",
                  {
                    "@type": "revdoc:Command",
                    "vdoc:content": [
                      "deploy-release"
                    ]
                  },
                  ")."
                ]
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        null,
        "Step 3 can be automated by tooling in particular domains as\n      a response to particularily formed git repository updates."
      ]
    },
    "files_layer": {
      "@id": "files_layer",
      "dc:title": "Files utility layer has files committed in git repositories",
      "@type": "vdoc:Chapter",
      "vdoc:content": [
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:Reference",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "git"
          ],
          "vdoc:ref": "https://git-scm.com/"
        },
        " is the industry standard\n      for version managing sets of files in a non-centralized ecosystem.\n      No additional tools are provided because there is no need.",
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-4.2.1"
              ]
            },
            ": ValOS tools should use git as the files provider."
          ]
        },
        "While github.com is the de facto standard provider and\n      the typical choice it must *not* be _required_.",
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-4.2.2"
              ]
            },
            ": All git providers must be fully supported by all ValOS\n          tools and libraries."
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    "packages_layer": {
      "@id": "packages_layer",
      "dc:title": "Packages utility layer has shared, versioned, dependable sets of files published as npmjs.com packages",
      "@type": "vdoc:Chapter",
      "vdoc:content": [
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-4.3.1"
              ]
            },
            ": The packages utility payload is ",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:Reference",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "npmjs.com packages"
              ],
              "vdoc:ref": "https://docs.npmjs.com/getting-started/packages"
            }
          ]
        },
        "These packages can be libraries, toolsets or prebuilt release\n      runtimes - any sets of files really. The raison d'être for\n      packages is when several different consumers depend on the same\n      set of files which are also expected to undergo periodic\n      development. The files thus need versioning, dependency\n      management and automated distribution - this all is provided by\n      npm.",
        null,
        "      Note: npmjs.com is a javascript repository - this should not be a\n      problem as long as ValOS remains mostly javascript and config\n      files. If a need to diversity the languages arises a ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:Reference",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "private npm registry"
          ],
          "vdoc:ref": "https://docs.npmjs.com/misc/registry#can-i-run-my-own-private-registry"
        },
        "can be set up for that purpose.",
        null,
        "      valma package commands: ",
        {
          "@type": "revdoc:Command",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "vlm assemble-packages"
          ]
        },
        " ",
        {
          "@type": "revdoc:Command",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "vlm publish-packages"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    "authorities_layer": {
      "@id": "authorities_layer",
      "dc:title": "Authorities utility layer has the authority deployments on infrastructure services",
      "@type": "vdoc:Chapter",
      "vdoc:content": [
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-4.4.1"
              ]
            },
            ": A ValOS ",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "authority"
              ]
            },
            " is uniquely identified by an\n            authority URI."
          ]
        },
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:Reference",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "Read more about valos URIs"
          ],
          "vdoc:ref": "packages/raem/README.md"
        },
        ".\n\n        ",
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-4.4.2"
              ]
            },
            ": A ValOS ",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "authority"
              ]
            },
            " can contain ValOS ",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "partitions"
              ]
            },
            " and must provide a mechanism for\n            accessing event logs and bvob content as well as for\n            accepting and authorizing incoming commands into authorized\n            partition events."
          ]
        },
        "Authorities are usually live deployments on some\n        infrastructure and they provide service APIs as the required\n        mechanisms.\n\n        Stateless or in some way non-infrastructural authorities also exist but\n        are specified elsewhere (they are considered degenerate, without\n        upstream and with empty payload).\n\n        ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:Reference",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "Read more about authorities"
          ],
          "vdoc:ref": "packages/sourcerer/README.md"
        },
        ".\n\n        ",
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-4.4.3"
              ]
            },
            ": Authorities utility layer payload (",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "authority payload"
              ]
            },
            ") is a set of deployed authority service APIs and any\n            associated static content."
          ]
        },
        "The payload here refers to the service deployments and their live APIs\n        themselves and not any dynamic content delivered through them. Such\n        dynamic content belongs to other domains (notably valospace content\n        resides in the ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "partitions"
          ]
        },
        " utility layer, see below).\n\n        The static content includes HTTP landing pages, site routes and their\n        configurations, ValOS gateway and plugin runtimes and any other similar\n        statically configured files.\n\n        ",
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-4.4.4"
              ]
            },
            ": An authority may have\n            an operations workspace (",
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "opspace"
              ]
            },
            ") as its\n            upstream for managing its payload."
          ]
        },
        "\n\n        Particular authorities are naturally free to implement their\n        operational architectures in any way they like. This said opspaces\n        have a well-defined structure which valma authority tools make use of.\n\n        Updates to the authority payloads are primarily done as modifications\n        to the corresponding opspace and then distributing those via release\n        deployments.\n\n        ",
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-4.4.5"
              ]
            },
            ": An opspace should not\n            be published as a package."
          ]
        },
        "\n\n        While opspaces make use of package.json and the npm dependency\n        management this provides, they can also contain considerable amounts of\n        static content. Also, there should be no reason to depend on\n        an opspace. Automatic release deployment systems should have access\n        to a opspace directly for building the release.\n\n        ",
        {
          "vdoc:blockquote": true,
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
              "vdoc:content": [
                "valos-vault-4.4.6"
              ]
            },
            ": Information must not\n            move from deployed authorities back to authority utility\n            layer upstream."
          ]
        },
        "\n\n        Information flowing back upstream increases complexity,\n        prevents decentralized and manual upstreams (there is a\n        definite upstream which must be always accessible), and are\n        a security concern (for programmatic access the downstream must\n        have the upstream credentials).\n\n        If a use case necessitating this arises, still seriously\n        consider keeping the mutateable content separate from the\n        upstream itself and instead have upstream only contain the\n        necessary code and credentials to access this content.\n\n        Note: this applies to architectural decisions and automations\n        only. Interactive content in valospace is not limited from\n        using an opspace to update authorities (although it is still\n        recommended to keep such valospace applications deployments\n        separate from the authorities they are used to control).\n\n        valma opspace commands: ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "vlm build-release"
          ]
        },
        " ",
        {
          "@type": "vdoc:CharacterData",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "vlm deploy-release"
          ]
        },
        {
          "dc:title": "ValOS core vs. auxiliary authorities",
          "@type": "vdoc:Chapter",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "ValOS authorities and any partition content they provide do\n        not need to be public. A ValOS core authority is an authority\n        which can be accessed using only ValOS core plugins (including\n        no plugins at all). A ValOS auxiliary authority is an authority\n        which requires a conforming but non-core ValOS gateway plugin\n        in order to be accessed. (Design Note 2019-03: the plugin\n        conformance requirements are unspecified. When they are\n        specified they must be lenient enough to enable sophisticated\n        protocols but constrained/sandboxed enough that gateway plugins\n        cannot interfere with other reasonably written plugins)."
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    "partitions_layer": {
      "@id": "partitions_layer",
      "dc:title": "Partitions utility layer - the foundation of valospace",
      "@type": "vdoc:Chapter",
      "vdoc:content": [
        "Event logs and bvob content are the partitions payload and are\n        consumed by ValOS gateways. It is more extensively covered\n        elsewhere and is mentioned here for completeness; precious\n        little infrastructural tooling is provided for them yet.\n\n        Eventually various partition diagnostics tools will come in handy:",
        {
          "vdoc:content": [
            {
              "@type": "vdoc:BulletList",
              "vdoc:entries": [
                [
                  "Media content import/export tools"
                ],
                [
                  "Complete partition to file system hierarchy save/load tools"
                ],
                [
                  "Event log introspection and manipulation tools"
                ],
                [
                  "etc."
                ]
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "dc:title": "ValOS public vs protected partitions",
          "@type": "vdoc:Chapter",
          "vdoc:content": [
            "All partitions provided by ValOS authorities are ValOS\n        partitions. Additionally ValOS public partitions are partitions\n        which are both",
            {
              "vdoc:content": [
                {
                  "@type": "vdoc:NumberedList",
                  "vdoc:entries": [
                    [
                      "provided by ValOS core authorities, and"
                    ],
                    [
                      "are available for an anonymous consumer with nothing but\n          a client capable of running the ValOS gateway runtime which\n          the authority itself provides (with reasonable concessions\n          for the authority to prevent DDOS attacks)"
                    ]
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            "TODO(iridian): Figure out whether this is the actually most\n                        meaningful place to put this semantic border.\n                        A specific term for non-authenticated\n                        partitions capable of running only on standard\n                        runtime is useful, but how useful actually?"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
